    <refsect1 xml:id="description"><title>Description</title>
        <para>
            <function>fma</function> performs, where possible, a fused multiply-add operation,
            returning <code>a * b + c</code>.
            In use cases where the return value is eventually consumed by a variable declared as
            <code>precise</code>:
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        <function>fma</function>() is considered a single operation, whereas the
                        expression <code>a * b + c</code> consumed by a variable declared as <code>precise</code>
                        is considered two operations.
                    </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        The precision of <function>fma</function>() can differ from the precision
                        of the expression <code>a * b + c</code>.
                    </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        <function>fma</function>() will be computed with the same precision as any
                        other <function>fma</function>() consumed by a <code>precise</code> variable,
                        giving invariant results for the same input values of <parameter>a</parameter>,
                        <parameter>b</parameter> and <parameter>c</parameter>.
                    </para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            Otherwise, in the absense of <code>precise</code> consumption, there are no
            special constraints on the number of operations or difference in precision between
            <function>fma</function>() and the expression <code>a * b + c</code>.
        </para>
    </refsect1>
